<subSubSection id="C36AD2BCFFDE0E7E24942D3EFB49F92A" pageId="5" pageNumber="536" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BCF8137FFDE0E7E24942D3EFB49F92A" blockId="5.[136,771,1386,1907]" lastBlockId="5.[816,1452,1386,1907]" pageId="5" pageNumber="536">
<emphasis id="B9045D25FFDE0E7E24942D3EFE52F9E9" box="[166,487,1585,1608]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="536">Description of the teleomorph</emphasis>
: Sori in all flowers of the inflorescences of 
<taxonomicName id="4C70FAB4FFDE0E7E25762D5CFE19F9CB" box="[324,428,1619,1642]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" genus="Tillandsia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="5" pageNumber="536" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9045D25FFDE0E7E25762D5CFE19F9CB" box="[324,428,1619,1642]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="536">Tillandsia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. suggesting systemic infection, 1 
<emphasis id="B9045D25FFDE0E7E24E32D7BFF6BF92A" box="[209,222,1652,1675]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="536">–</emphasis>
2 cm long, producing naked, dusty spore masses around the rudimentary developed innermost floral organs 
<emphasis id="B9045D25FFDE0E7E26DA2D9AFCB6F90D" box="[744,771,1685,1708]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="536">—staminal</emphasis>
filaments and ovary remain partly intact in the sorus center, anthers not developed, peridium lacking, sori protected only by closed perianths and bracts. Spores usually single, sometimes glued together forming small groups, variable in color, shape, and size (also between collections, see 
<tableCitation id="C6F2B48CFFDE0E7E26952C34FD41F8F3" box="[679,756,1851,1874]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="2.[136,188,155,175]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Table 1 List of examined specimens of the sexual stage of Pattersoniomyces tillandsiae, with host species, spore size range, mean spore size with standard deviation, GenBank accesion number, and reference specimen" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF0FD1BFFFD90E7924BA2B94FD4FFF6B" pageId="5" pageNumber="536" tableUuid="DF0FD1BFFFD90E7924BA2B94FD4FFF6B">Table 1</tableCitation>
), pale brown to olive-brown, globose or subglobose, more or less collapsed or hemispherically cupped, (5.0 
<emphasis id="B9045D25FFDE0E7E21532E65FADBFA20" box="[1377,1390,1386,1409]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="536">–</emphasis>
)6.0 
<emphasis id="B9045D25FFDE0E7E21AC2E65FA1EFA20" box="[1438,1451,1386,1409]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="536">–</emphasis>
11.5(−16.0) × 5.0 
<emphasis id="B9045D25FFDE0E7E27D72E83FC47FA02" box="[997,1010,1420,1443]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="536">–</emphasis>
10.5 μm, usually with one or exceptionally two spherical bodies (lipid granules) in the cytoplasm; wall even 0.4 
<emphasis id="B9045D25FFDE0E7E27B52EC1FC21FA44" box="[903,916,1486,1509]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="536">–</emphasis>
0.8(−1.0) μm thick, somewhat darker than the rest of spore, often somewhat lighter on one side, surface variably ornamented, smooth or with brittle epispore breaking up into thin polygonal areas, cracked or covered with fine ridges as seen by LM, almost smooth, granulose or covered with fine, circular, or irregular ridges as seen by SEM.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
